Oskar Hergt has been re-elected once again. However, he and the national conservatives within the party are increasingly looking toward alliances with forces to their right, as their previous hostility toward the <span style="color: #003755;">**DNF**</span> continues to fade. Furthermore, the bourgeois elites influencing the party have pushed its leadership to reconsider some form of cooperation with the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>, aiming to integrate them as a "constructive component of the state" through a so-called 'taming' strategy.

Recently, discussions have emerged about a new referendum—one designed to unite the German right, much like the Young Plan referendum attempted, but this time focused on prematurely dissolving the Prussian Landtag. Given the radicalized political climate, such a move would allow the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>, which currently holds a meager [+ nsdap_r_prussia +] seats, to make significant gains.

